When I specify multiple issuer/audience requirements on an API/method, eg. as in :
```
@endpoints.api(
    name='greeting',
    version='v1',
    issuers={
        'shell_service_account': ServiceAccountIssuer(SHELL_SERVICE_ACCOUNT),
        'default_service_account': ServiceAccountIssuer(DEFAULT_SERVICE_ACCOUNT),
    },
    audiences={
        'shell_service_account': [AUDIENCE],
        'default_service_account': [AUDIENCE],
    },
)
class GreetingApi(remote.Service):
    ...
```

the generated OpenAPI spec requires all issuers at once, which sounds incorrect:
```
        "security": [
          {
            "default_service_account-9a49f844": [],
            "shell_service_account-9a49f844": []
          }
        ]
```

Instead, I would expect the security requirement to be an OR of each individual issuer/audience requirement:
```
        "security": [
          {
            "default_service_account-9a49f844": []
          },
          {
            "shell_service_account-9a49f844": []
          }
        ]
```

I've noticed something with the google-endpoints package, which I hope will be of interest...

I believe that endpoints-python/endpoints/swagger_generator.py may be in need of some modification. Here's why:

I've written a protorpc message class that has some required fields on it, such as:

```
class MyClass(messages.Message):
    my_field = messages.StringField(1, required=True)
```

When I use the swagger generator, I get a swagger output similar to this:

```
"definitions": {
    "MyClass": {
        "properties": {
            "my_field": {
                "required": true,
                "type": "string"
            }
        },
        "type": "object"
    }
}
```


If it weren't for the "required" attribute, the above would work fine. However, when it is there, I get the following error when I try to gcloud beta service-management deploy the swagger spec:

> "Invalid Swagger spec. Please fix the schema errors:\n\"/definitions/
> ...
> 
> ...
> required\": domain: validation; keyword: type; message: instance has incorrect type; expected: [\"array\"]; found: \"boolean\""


Upon reviewing the OpenAPI spec, I noted that for schema objects, JSON Schema structure should be used, which places the required properties in an array.

http://json-schema.org/latest/json-schema-validation.html#rfc.section.5.15

So, I took my required properties for each of my definitions, and put them in an array, similar to this:

```
"definitions": {
    "MyClass": {
        "properties": {
            "my_field": {
                "type": "string"
            },
            "my_other_field": {
                "type": "string"
            }
        },
        "type": "object",
        "required": [
            "my_field",
            "my_other_field"
        ]
    }
}

```

Then, I tried to deploy the swagger spec again, and it worked!

So, in short, I think the swagger_generator may need change the way that it declares the required fields in the output. If there aren't any required fields defined, everything works fine. When there are, gcloud returns errors.

I'm on:
gcloud v133.0.0
google-endpoints v2.0.0b4
